What it is: NAT is like a receptionist at an office. Your private network (home/office) uses internal IPs that the internet canâ€™t see. NAT takes your internal IP and translates it to a public IP before sending data to the internet.
Why we use it:
âœ… Saves IPv4 addresses
âœ… Hides internal devices for security
Example: Your phone (192.168.1.10) wants to visit google.com. The router uses NAT to send the request using its public IP (e.g., 49.204.xx.xx). Google replies to the router, and the router knows which device to forward it to.
