What it is: ARP is like asking, â€œHey, who has this IP address? Tell me your MAC!â€
Purpose: It finds the MAC address of a device when you only know its IP address.
Example: Your computer wants to send data to 192.168.1.5. It broadcasts an ARP request. The device with that IP replies with its MAC address.
ğŸ”‘ MAC Address (Media Access Control)

What it is: A MAC address is like your deviceâ€™s fingerprint â€“ a unique ID burned into the network card.
Format: Usually looks like 00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E.
Role: Used within the local network to identify devices. Even if you change your IP, the MAC stays the same (unless spoofed).
ğŸŒ IPv4

What it is: The 4th version of the Internet Protocol. It uses 32-bit addresses, which look like 192.168.1.1.
Limitation: Only about 4.3 billion unique addresses, which is not enough for todayâ€™s internet.
Fun fact: Thatâ€™s why NAT became popular â€“ to share one public IP among many devices.
